abstract: The radial distributions of atom pairs in water and in solutions of hydrochloric acid have been measured by x-ray diffraction. The near-neighbor water correlations are strongly affected by the ions. Part of the experimental distributions is attributed to new oxygen-to-oxygen distances, associated with the presence of excess protons, and these distances become shorter as the concentration of the acid increases.

The material obtained from these investigations has indicated to the writer that the area studied offers extremely valuable opportunities for helminthological and protozoological work. The data obtained will serve as the basis for several important papers which will be published in the near future.
